{"word":"στονόεις","slug":"στονόεις","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>στονόεις</b></el> <el>(στονόεις, εσσα, εν) </el><br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:στόνος'><el>στόνος</el></a>\n<p/><div class='li750'><b>1. </b><i>causing groans</i> or <i>sighs</i>, <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b>generally, <i>mournful, sad, wretched</i>, <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>; <a href='S:neuter'>neut.</a> as <a href='S:Adverb'>adv.</a>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}